column1: #Text=Sawai Madhopur is in the Bharatpur Division of Rajasthan .
#Text=Sawai Madhopur was founded by and named after Sawai Madho Singh I in 1763 .
#Text=The current population of the city is approximately 125,000 people .
#Text=It is generally used by travelers as a place to stay while visiting Ranthambore , 11 km away .

#Text=There are direct connections by train between Sawai Madhopur and Kota ( 1.5 hours ) , Jaipur ( 2 hours ) , Bharatpur ( 3 hours ) , Ajmer ( 4 hours ) , Delhi ( 4+ hours ) , Agra ( 5 hours ) , and Mumbai ( 13 hours ) .
#Text=Buses to Jaipur ( 6 hours ) leave several times per day from a bus stand located near the overpass .
#Text=Traveling by bus from Jaipur to Sawai Madhopur is not recommended .
#Text=The buses are very slow , dirty and uncomfortable ; the train is clearly a better option .
#Text=The city can be explored by foot .
#Text=Most visitors to Sawai Madhopur visit nearby Ranthambore , which has a fort and a famous national park .
#Text=However , there are several attractions within the city :
#Text=Trinetra Ganesh Temple , Opposite Hotel hill View Ranthambore Road ( take a car or Jeep from Sawai Madhopur railway station ; the distance is 12 km ) , ☏ +919587030211 , ✉ tigeroath@gmail.com .
#Text=Rajiv Gandhi Regional Museum of Natural History .
#Text=Chamatkar Temple ( 3 km from the railway station ) .
#Text=Bhairon Temple ( on top of the hill ) .
#Text=Take a safari to the national park in nearby Ranthambore .
#Text=Cheetal Handicrafts , Ranthambhore Road ( Opposite the Hotel Regency ) , ☏ +917462223196 , ✉ vicky_ranthambhore@yahoo.com .
#Text=A project to provide income to local women by having them produce and sell handmade works including beautiful blockprints , bedsheats , covers , and clothes .
#Text=Items can also be purchased online from the website .
#Text=Similar to Dastkar , this is a project that provides local women an opportunity to earn income by producing crafts .
#Text=Items can also be purchased online from the website .
#Text=An NGO founded by M. D. Parashar , you can buy paintings of tigers produced by the founder .
#Text=Almost every hotel and restaurant serves alcohol and coffee .
#Text=There are also several alcohol stores on ranthambhore road near the hotels .
#Text=Many hotels are located on the edge of the city on Ranthambhore Road .
#Text=Safari operators will pick up from these hotels by jeep for visits to Ranthambore .
#Text=It is best to book online on local indian websites like goibibo , which include more hotels and often much cheaper rates .
#Text=Pink palace , right after the " T " shaped overpass south west of the train station .
#Text=IT 's actually in the city which might be a plus .
#Text=Cheaper rates can usually be found online , making this one of the cheapest hotels in the area .
#Text=Hammir Wild Life Resort , Ranthambore Road , ☏ +917462220562 , ✉ info@hammirwildliferesorts.com .
#Text=Single ₹1,600 in offseason , ₹2,300 in high season ; double ₹2,600 in offseason , ₹2,990 in high season .
#Text=Former summer rest house of Jaipur rulers .
#Text=Off the beaten path and a bit harder to find .
#Text=Pugmark Resort , Village Khilchipur Ranthambhore ( Next to the Nahargarh Ranthambhore ) , ☏ +917462252205 , ✉ resort@thepugmark.net .
#Text=Nice setting with a pool , but the rooms are dated .
#Text=Ranthambore Forest Resort , Ranthambhore Road ( Near Vivekanandapuram Colony ) , ☏ +917462221120 , ✉ reservations@ranthambhoreforestresort.in .
#Text=Friendly and welcoming ; good Indian food in the restaurant .
#Text=Ranthambore Haveli , Ranthambore Road ( Opposite FCI Godown ) , ☏ +919001576609 .
#Text=Built to resemble an old hunting lodge .
#Text=Luxurious tents , with a private butler to assist you .
#Text=Anuraga Palace , A Treehouse Palace Hotel , Ranthambhore Road , ☏ +919718313838 , ✉ sales@treehousehotels.in .
#Text=Nahargarh Ranthambhore , Village Khilchipur , Ranthambhore Road ( Just northeast of Sawai Modhopur , 8 km west from Ranthambore ) , ☏ +917462252281 , ✉ alsisar@sify.com .
#Text=Luxurious tented camp designed to mirror the experiences that 19th-century princes had while on safari .
#Text=It was built in the 1920s as a hunting lodge for the Maharaja of Jaipur .
